snippet.textDisplay: I bet your assessment was right! When it comes to the science of the storms, you need that convective energy (warm, buoyant air) to have as much lifting energy as possible, so the warmer it is the better, and the more ways it has to rise aid in forming a tornado. If there is not enough energy to lift the parcel of air upwards at a rate that overcomes the cooling effect from the cold pool, the cold air will essentially cut off the formation of a tornado. On the other side of the coin, you also need at least some of that very cold air coming from the back of the storm (rear flank downdraft) to aid in producing that low level shear to cause rotation. If you noticed, your original fan setup produced the best results because the fan by the hot bucket was lifting the warmer air upward while the other fan was pushing cold air into the warmer, rising air, causing the shear necessary in creating rotation. So, if you redid the experiment, I bet if you had the hot water bucket with less ice and the fan closer and pointing up, and the cold bucket with more ice and the fan pushing air towards the warm air, you may see it work a bit better!
snippet.textOriginal: I bet your assessment was right! When it comes to the science of the storms, you need that convective energy (warm, buoyant air) to have as much lifting energy as possible, so the warmer it is the better, and the more ways it has to rise aid in forming a tornado. If there is not enough energy to lift the parcel of air upwards at a rate that overcomes the cooling effect from the cold pool, the cold air will essentially cut off the formation of a tornado. On the other side of the coin, you also need at least some of that very cold air coming from the back of the storm (rear flank downdraft) to aid in producing that low level shear to cause rotation. If you noticed, your original fan setup produced the best results because the fan by the hot bucket was lifting the warmer air upward while the other fan was pushing cold air into the warmer, rising air, causing the shear necessary in creating rotation. So, if you redid the experiment, I bet if you had the hot water bucket with less ice and the fan closer and pointing up, and the cold bucket with more ice and the fan pushing air towards the warm air, you may see it work a bit better!
